    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm stuck on a section of my dissertation. I've got a result where the p-value is 0.06. My advisor says it's \"not statistically significant,\" but there's a really clear trend in the visual data. Can you explain why we can't just call this a significant finding? Also, how much of this is just due to random noise in the sample?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06 does not meet the conventional threshold for statistical significance, which is usually set at $p < 0.05$. This means that while your data shows a trend, there is a 6% chance of observing this result even if there is truly no effect in the population. The difference between 0.06 and 0.05 often reflects the inherent uncertainty and variability, which is a form of random noise, in your sample. To address this, you might discuss the \"marginal significance\" or simply report the effect size alongside the p-value to showcase the strength of the trend observed.",
