    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense, but it feels a bit arbitrary. If the difference between 0.05 and 0.06 is only 1%, why does that change the entire interpretation of the study? It feels like the \"noise\" is just obscuring something real. Can you go deeper into what that noise actually represents in terms of the null hypothesis? Like, what is the noise physically doing to the data to make a real trend look like it's just a fluke?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The noise, in this context, represents the random variation inherent in the data collection process and the differences between individual subjects that aren't related to your intervention. The null hypothesis, which assumes *no* real effect, is what we are testing against; the noise is the mechanism that allows the data to fluctuate randomly around that null expectation. A higher level of noise, perhaps due to a smaller sample size or high within-group variability, makes it harder to distinguish a genuine, true signal (the effect) from the natural, random background chatter. In essence, the noise is the \"unexplained\" variance that the statistical test cannot confidently separate from the \"explained\" variance of your hypothesized effect.",
      "source": "target",
